This paper focuses on developing an automated framework for detecting relative afferent pupillary defect (RAPD) using deep learning-based algorithms. Therefore, the most likely arXiv CS sub-category is cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition). The paper also involves transfer learning, which is a popular technique in machine learning, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. The study involves a clinical study with a lab-on-a-headset, which falls under the sub-category cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). The paper also discusses optic nerve disorders, which can be related to neuroscience and neuroengineering, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the assessment of pupillary light reflex, which can be related to ophthalmology and optometry, making cs.HL (Hardware Architecture) another possible sub-category.
